<p>In the conventional way we would define a condition in the <code>while</code> loop parenthesis <code>()</code> and a terminating condition inside the braces <code>{}</code>, but <code>--&gt;</code> defines both at once.</p>

<p>For example:</p>

<pre><code>int abc(void)
{
    int a = 5
    while((a--) &gt; 0) // Decrement and comparison both at once
    {
        // Code
    }
}
</code></pre>

<p>This decrements <code>a</code> and runs the loop while <code>a</code> is greater than <code>0</code>.</p>

<p>Conventionally, it would be like:</p>

<pre><code>int abc(void)
{
    int a = 5;
    while(a &gt; 0)
    {
        a--;
        // Code
    }
    a--;
}
</code></pre>

<p>Both ways, we do the same thing and achieve the same goals.</p>
